result.execSummary:
Bridget A. Mueske was extradited to another county, state or jurisdiction. Extradition means Bridget A. Mueske was accused or convicted of an offense in another county, state or jurisdiction and was taken there to face their charge(s) or conviction.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt: This did not take place. Court event needs to be in court record to dispose of case.

11:03 AM Defendant Bridget A. Mueske in court, in custody.  Halle E. Hatch appeared for the State of Wisconsin. Attorney Liesl Nelson appeared in court via phone. Defendant has copy of complaint. Atty Nelson: spoke with Def last week re: hoping to post cash bond in Minnesota.  Court goes over Defendant's rights re: extradition process.   Constitutional rights explained to defendant  Exam'd re: understanding of law, penalty and rights. Defendant wishes to waiver her right to extradition and return to Washington County Minnesota.   Court finds Defendant freely, intelligently, knowingly, and understandingly made and waives constitutional right to extradition. Defendant signs waiver. Court will sign waiver once presented. 11:09
